title: LCQ13: Pigs died of foot-and-mouth disease
secretary_name: Secretary for the Environment and Food, Mrs Lily Yam
question_text: Following  is a question by Dr Hon. Tang Siu-tong and a written reply by the Secretary for the Environment and Food, Mrs Lily Yam, in the Legislative Council meeting (March 28):

Question With regard to cases of pigs being infected with the foot-and-mouth disease, will the Government inform this Council of: (a) the respective numbers of pigs which died of the disease and the farms affected in each month of the past three years; and (b) the time normally taken by the relevant departments to remove carcasses of pigs which died of the disease upon receiving reports of such pig carcasses being disposed of in public places, and the measures in place to stop pig farmers from dumping pig carcasses anywhere they like?

574 (b)	Under normal circumstances, after Food and Environmental Hygiene Department (FEHD) has received reports on illegal dumping of pig carcasses in public places, it can remove the carcasses within three hours or a shorter period. Pig carcasses are trade waste and pig farmers should be responsible for transporting them to landfills for disposal.  However, to safeguard public hygiene and to help pig farmers to dispose of pig carcasses properly, FEHD employs a contractor to collect pig carcasses at 78 designated collection points in the New Territories and to transport them to the landfills.  AFCD has issued letters to advise

the New Territories and to transport them to the landfills.  AFCD has issued letters to advise pig farmers that pig carcasses should be disposed of at the designated collection points and reinforced the message during regular farm inspections. FEHD will prosecute persons who dump pig carcasses illegally under the Public Cleansing and Prevention of Nuisances Regulation (Cap.132 Sub. Leg.BK). The maximum penalties are a fine of $25,000 and six-month imprisonment. (Note1) With proper care, the pigs which contracted FMD were recovered and did not die. (Note 2) They were mainly pigs belonging to a large farm

recovered and did not die. (Note 2) They were mainly pigs belonging to a large farm on which the vaccination practices recommended by AFCD were not followed.  In view of this, AFCD has strengthened its works on vaccination to control FMD more effectively.  Last year, AFCD conducted applied research and recommended the most appropriate vaccination programmes to all pig farmers prior to the FMD season.  It will further provide training to them to promote proper vaccination technique. Wednesday, March 28, 2001 Question
